  <conbody>
<section id="what-publishing-means-in-dita">
<title>What publishing means in DITA</title>
<p>DITA is a <b>source format</b>, not an output. Publishing is the process of:</p>
<ul>
  <li>resolving references (conref/keyref),</li>
  <li>applying filtering rules,</li>
  <li>transforming XML into HTML/PDF/other formats,</li>
  <li>applying styling and navigation rules,</li>
  <li>producing deliverables that match your product and brand.</li>
</ul>
<p>Many DITA programs use the <b>DITA Open Toolkit (DITA‑OT)</b> as the publishing engine. Others use CCMS publishing services that may internally rely on DITA‑OT or custom pipelines.</p>
<p>This topic focuses on practical publishing with DITA‑OT because it is widely used and teaches you the core concepts that apply everywhere.</p>
</section>
<section id="inputs-and-outputs-what-dita-ot-expects">
<title>Inputs and outputs: what DITA-OT expects</title>
<p><b>Input</b></p>
<p>DITA‑OT publishes from a <b>map</b> (most common) or a single topic. In professional workflows:</p>
<ul>
  <li>maps are preferred because they define structure, keys, and context.</li>
</ul>
<p><b>Output formats (common)</b></p>
<ul>
  <li><b>HTML5</b>: website-like output with navigation</li>
  <li><b>PDF</b>: often XSL‑FO based (toolchain-dependent)</li>
  <li>Other outputs via plugins or extensions</li>
</ul>
<p><b>The key idea</b></p>
<p>A map is not just a TOC; it is the <b>publication definition</b>. If you publish the same topic under two different maps, you can get different results because:</p>
<ul>
  <li>key definitions differ,</li>
  <li>filtering differs,</li>
  <li>navigation context differs.</li>
</ul>
</section>
<section id="the-build-pipeline-steps-what-happens-during-publishing">
<title>The “build pipeline” steps (what happens during publishing)</title>
<p>Publishing is more than “transform XML to HTML.”</p>
<p>A typical pipeline includes:</p>
<ol>
  <li><b>Preprocess</b> — parse the map, resolve topicrefs, collect key definitions, gather referenced topics and resources.</li>
  <li><b>Reference resolution</b> — apply conref pulls, resolve keyrefs, validate IDs and targets.</li>
  <li><b>Filtering</b> — include/exclude content based on rules, adjust link targets accordingly.</li>
  <li><b>Transform</b> — generate intermediate or final formats, apply templates and rules for HTML/PDF.</li>
  <li><b>Postprocess</b> — create navigation and search index assets, copy images/media, apply final styling.</li>
</ol>
<p>Understanding these stages helps you debug issues:</p>
<ul>
  <li>missing content (filtering),</li>
  <li>broken links (IDs, key spaces),</li>
  <li>wrong product name (keys),</li>
  <li>missing images (resource paths).</li>
</ul>
</section>
<section id="basic-dita-ot-commands-the-8020">
<title>Basic DITA-OT commands (the 80/20)</title>
<p><b>Publish HTML5</b></p>
<codeblock outputclass="language-bash">dita -i maps/guides/getting-started.ditamap -f html5 -o out/html</codeblock>
<p><b>Publish PDF (if configured)</b></p>
<codeblock outputclass="language-bash">dita -i maps/guides/getting-started.ditamap -f pdf -o out/pdf</codeblock>
<p><b>Practical tips</b></p>
<ul>
  <li>Always use an explicit output directory (<codeph>-o</codeph>).</li>
  <li>Keep your build artifacts out of your source tree where possible.</li>
  <li>Use a consistent build script so builds are repeatable.</li>
</ul>
</section>
<section id="repeatable-builds-project-files-and-build-scripts">
<title>Repeatable builds: project files and build scripts</title>
<p>As soon as you have:</p>
<ul>
  <li>multiple deliverables,</li>
  <li>filtering variants,</li>
  <li>consistent parameters,</li>
</ul>
<p>…you should formalize builds.</p>
<p><b>Why repeatability matters</b></p>
<p>Repeatable builds ensure:</p>
<ul>
  <li>anyone can build the same output,</li>
  <li>CI builds match local builds,</li>
  <li>releases are reproducible.</li>
</ul>
<p><b>A typical approach</b></p>
<ul>
  <li>Create a build script (<codeph>build.sh</codeph> or <codeph>build.ps1</codeph>) that runs defined publications.</li>
  <li>Use DITA‑OT project files (where supported in your version) or a wrapper configuration.</li>
</ul>
<p>Even without deep customization, a script with consistent parameters eliminates “works on my machine” issues.</p>
</section>
<section id="parameters-controlling-output-behavior">
<title>Parameters: controlling output behavior</title>
<p>DITA‑OT allows parameters to control:</p>
<ul>
  <li>toc depth,</li>
  <li>chunking behavior,</li>
  <li>navigation,</li>
  <li>filtering integration,</li>
  <li>output artifacts.</li>
</ul>
<p>In practice, you’ll maintain:</p>
<ul>
  <li>a baseline parameter set for HTML,</li>
  <li>a baseline parameter set for PDF,</li>
  <li>variant overrides per product/platform.</li>
</ul>
<p><b>Common DITA-OT parameters (all transtypes)</b></p>
<p>These parameters work across most output formats:</p>
<simpletable>
  <sthead>
    <stentry>Parameter</stentry>
    <stentry>Values / Example</stentry>
    <stentry>What it does</stentry>
  </sthead>
  <strow>
    <stentry><codeph>-i</codeph> / <codeph>--input</codeph></stentry>
    <stentry><codeph>maps/book.ditamap</codeph></stentry>
    <stentry>Input map or topic file</stentry>
  </strow>
  <strow>
    <stentry><codeph>-f</codeph> / <codeph>--format</codeph></stentry>
    <stentry><codeph>html5</codeph>, <codeph>pdf</codeph>, <codeph>xhtml</codeph></stentry>
    <stentry>Output transtype</stentry>
  </strow>
  <strow>
    <stentry><codeph>-o</codeph> / <codeph>--output</codeph></stentry>
    <stentry><codeph>out/html5</codeph></stentry>
    <stentry>Output directory</stentry>
  </strow>
  <strow>
    <stentry><codeph>--filter</codeph></stentry>
    <stentry><codeph>build/ditaval/web.ditaval</codeph></stentry>
    <stentry>DITAVAL filter file for conditional processing</stentry>
  </strow>
  <strow>
    <stentry><codeph>--propertyfile</codeph></stentry>
    <stentry><codeph>build/html5.properties</codeph></stentry>
    <stentry>Load parameters from a properties file</stentry>
  </strow>
  <strow>
    <stentry><codeph>--processing-mode</codeph></stentry>
    <stentry><codeph>strict</codeph>, <codeph>lax</codeph>, <codeph>skip</codeph></strow>
    <stentry>How to handle errors (<codeph>strict</codeph> = fail on warnings)</stentry>
  </strow>
  <strow>
    <stentry><codeph>--temp</codeph></stentry>
    <stentry><codeph>/tmp/dita-temp</codeph></stentry>
    <stentry>Temporary directory (useful for debugging)</stentry>
  </strow>
  <strow>
    <stentry><codeph>-v</codeph> / <codeph>--verbose</codeph></strow>
    <stentry><i>(flag)</i></strow>
    <stentry>Enable verbose logging</strow>
  </strow>
  <strow>
    <stentry><codeph>--debug</codeph></strow>
    <stentry><i>(flag)</i></strow>
    <stentry>Enable debug logging (very detailed)</strow>
  </strow>
</simpletable>
<p><b>HTML5-specific parameters</b></p>
<simpletable>
  <sthead>
    <stentry>Parameter</stentry>
    <stentry>Values / Example</stentry>
    <stentry>What it does</stentry>
  </sthead>
  <strow>
    <stentry><codeph>--nav-toc</codeph></strow>
    <stentry><codeph>none</codeph>, <codeph>partial</codeph>, <codeph>full</codeph></strow>
    <stentry>Table of contents generation in each page</strow>
  </strow>
  <strow>
    <stentry><codeph>--args.copycss</codeph></strow>
    <stentry><codeph>yes</codeph>, <codeph>no</codeph></strow>
    <stentry>Copy custom CSS to output directory</strow>
  </strow>
  <strow>
    <stentry><codeph>--args.css</codeph></strow>
    <stentry><codeph>brand.css</codeph></strow>
    <stentry>Name of custom CSS file to link</strow>
  </strow>
  <strow>
    <stentry><codeph>--args.cssroot</codeph></strow>
    <stentry><codeph>css/</codeph></strow>
    <stentry>Source directory for CSS files</strow>
  </strow>
  <strow>
    <stentry><codeph>--args.csspath</codeph></strow>
    <stentry><codeph>css</codeph></strow>
    <stentry>Path in output where CSS is placed</strow>
  </strow>
  <strow>
    <stentry><codeph>--args.hdr</codeph></strow>
    <stentry><codeph>header.xml</codeph></strow>
    <stentry>Custom header file for every page</strow>
  </strow>
  <strow>
    <stentry><codeph>--args.ftr</codeph></strow>
    <stentry><codeph>footer.xml</codeph></strow>
    <stentry>Custom footer file for every page</strow>
  </strow>
  <strow>
    <stentry><codeph>--args.gen.task.lbl</codeph></strow>
    <stentry><codeph>YES</codeph>, <codeph>NO</codeph></strow>
    <stentry>Generate step labels (&quot;Step 1&quot;, &quot;Step 2&quot;)</strow>
  </strow>
  <strow>
    <stentry><codeph>--args.rellinks</codeph></strow>
    <stentry><codeph>none</codeph>, <codeph>all</codeph>, <codeph>nofamily</codeph></strow>
    <stentry>Which related links to include</strow>
  </strow>
  <strow>
    <stentry><codeph>--args.outext</codeph></strow>
    <stentry><codeph>.html</codeph></strow>
    <stentry>Output file extension</strow>
  </strow>
</simpletable>
<p><b>PDF-specific parameters</b></p>
<simpletable>
  <sthead>
    <stentry>Parameter</stentry>
    <stentry>Values / Example</stentry>
    <stentry>What it does</stentry>
  </sthead>
  <strow>
    <stentry><codeph>--args.bookmap-order</codeph></strow>
    <stentry><codeph>discard</codeph>, <codeph>retain</codeph></strow>
    <stentry>Keep or discard bookmap element order</strow>
  </strow>
  <strow>
    <stentry><codeph>--args.chapter.layout</codeph></strow>
    <stentry><codeph>MINITOC</codeph>, <codeph>BASIC</codeph></strow>
    <stentry>Chapter page layout style</strow>
  </strow>
  <strow>
    <stentry><codeph>--args.fo.userconfig</codeph></strow>
    <stentry><codeph>fop.xconf</codeph></strow>
    <stentry>FOP configuration file</strow>
  </strow>
  <strow>
    <stentry><codeph>--custom.xep.config</codeph></strow>
    <stentry><codeph>xep.xml</codeph></strow>
    <stentry>XEP formatter configuration</strow>
  </strow>
  <strow>
    <stentry><codeph>--pdf.version</codeph></strow>
    <stentry><codeph>1.5</codeph>, <codeph>1.7</codeph></strow>
    <stentry>PDF version to generate</strow>
  </strow>
</simpletable>
<p><b>Using a properties file (recommended for teams)</b></p>
<p>Instead of long command lines, put stable settings in a <codeph>.properties</codeph> file:</p>
<codeblock outputclass="language-properties"># build/html5-sidebar.properties
nav-toc           = full
args.copycss      = yes
args.cssroot      = css/
args.css          = brand.css
args.gen.task.lbl = YES
args.rellinks     = nofamily</codeblock>
<p>Then build with:</p>
<codeblock outputclass="language-bash">dita -i maps/book.ditamap -f html5 -o out/html5 \
  --propertyfile=build/html5-sidebar.properties \
  --filter=build/ditaval/web.ditaval</codeblock>
<p><b>Example: passing parameters (Ant-style)</b></p>
<codeblock outputclass="language-bash">dita -i maps/guides/getting-started.ditamap -f html5 -o out/html \
  -Dargs.gen.task.lbl=true \
  -Dargs.rellinks=none</codeblock>
<note><b>Note:</b> The <codeph>-D</codeph> prefix syntax is the Ant-style parameter passing. The <codeph>--args.*</codeph> syntax is recommended for DITA-OT 3.x+.</note>
<p>The exact parameters you use depend on your output requirements and your DITA-OT version.</p>
</section>
<section id="filtering-in-the-build-ditaval-concept">
<title>Filtering in the build (DITAVAL concept)</title>
<p>Filtering is usually applied at build time by providing filtering rules.</p>
<p>Typical workflow:</p>
<ol>
  <li>Tag content with attributes (<codeph>platform=&quot;windows&quot;</codeph>).</li>
  <li>Create a filter file that includes/excludes values.</li>
  <li>Run separate builds for each variant.</li>
</ol>
<p><b>Example build strategy</b></p>
<ul>
  <li><codeph>build-windows-html</codeph></li>
  <li><codeph>build-linux-html</codeph></li>
  <li><codeph>build-windows-pdf</codeph></li>
  <li><codeph>build-linux-pdf</codeph></li>
</ul>
<p>Even if you later automate this, it’s valuable to think of variants as explicit publications.</p>
</section>
<section id="output-customization-where-to-change-what">
<title>Output customization: where to change what</title>
<p><b>HTML customization</b></p>
<p>Common customization areas:</p>
<ul>
  <li>CSS (theme),</li>
  <li>HTML templates and headers/footers,</li>
  <li>navigation behavior,</li>
  <li>search integration (depending on output).</li>
</ul>
<p>A practical approach:</p>
<ul>
  <li>start with CSS and minimal HTML template overrides,</li>
  <li>avoid deep XSLT changes until necessary.</li>
</ul>
<p><b>PDF customization</b></p>
<p>PDF often requires:</p>
<ul>
  <li>FO styling rules,</li>
  <li>page masters, headers/footers,</li>
  <li>tables and code block formatting,</li>
  <li>numbering and cross-references.</li>
</ul>
<p>PDF customization can become a deep specialization area. Start small:</p>
<ul>
  <li>change fonts, margins, headers,</li>
  <li>adjust table styles,</li>
  <li>make code blocks readable.</li>
</ul>
<p>Then expand:</p>
<ul>
  <li>custom cover pages,</li>
  <li>running headers and footers,</li>
  <li>index generation and glossaries (if your pipeline supports them).</li>
</ul>
<p><b>Plugin customization</b></p>
<p>DITA‑OT supports plugins to:</p>
<ul>
  <li>add new transforms,</li>
  <li>override templates,</li>
  <li>inject preprocessing steps,</li>
  <li>create reports.</li>
</ul>
<p>Use plugins when:</p>
<ul>
  <li>you need consistent custom behavior across builds,</li>
  <li>you want to package customization cleanly,</li>
  <li>parameter overrides aren’t enough.</li>
</ul>
</section>
<section id="debugging-build-problems-a-practical-checklist">
<title>Debugging build problems (a practical checklist)</title>
<p><b>Problem: Content missing</b></p>
<ul>
  <li>Check filtering rules.</li>
  <li>Check map inclusion (topicref points to correct file).</li>
  <li>Check if a topic is excluded by conditional processing attributes.</li>
  <li>Check if content is pulled via conref and the target is missing.</li>
</ul>
<p><b>Problem: Broken links or unresolved references</b></p>
<ul>
  <li>Validate IDs and references.</li>
  <li>Ensure topic IDs and element IDs exist.</li>
  <li>Check for renames that weren’t propagated.</li>
</ul>
<p><b>Problem: Wrong product name or wrong URL</b></p>
<ul>
  <li>Check keys in the map.</li>
  <li>Ensure you are building the correct map.</li>
  <li>Check key scopes if advanced map structures exist.</li>
</ul>
<p><b>Problem: Images missing</b></p>
<ul>
  <li>Ensure image paths are correct and copied into output.</li>
  <li>Ensure images are referenced with correct relative paths.</li>
  <li>Check whether filtering excludes topics that provide the images.</li>
</ul>
<p><b>Problem: PDF formatting issues</b></p>
<ul>
  <li>Inspect FO output if accessible.</li>
  <li>Identify whether the problem is content structure (tables, code blocks) or styling.</li>
  <li>Apply minimal overrides first.</li>
</ul>
</section>
<section id="ci-and-automation-publishing-like-software">
<title>CI and automation: publishing like software</title>
<p>A mature DITA pipeline looks like software CI:</p>
<ul>
  <li>builds are triggered by commits,</li>
  <li>validation runs automatically,</li>
  <li>outputs are versioned and deployed.</li>
</ul>
<p><b>Practical CI steps</b></p>
<ol>
  <li>Validate XML (well-formed + schema/DTD as applicable).</li>
  <li>Run DITA‑OT build for each required publication.</li>
  <li>Fail if warnings exceed a threshold (ideally fail on unresolved refs).</li>
  <li>Publish artifacts to:</li>
</ol>
<p>   - documentation portal,    - release package,    - internal storage.</p>
<p><b>Output deployment patterns</b></p>
<ul>
  <li>Static site hosting for HTML outputs,</li>
  <li>artifact repositories for PDFs,</li>
  <li>CCMS publishing service for enterprise portals.</li>
</ul>
</section>
<section id="professional-publishing-architecture-how-doc-teams-scale">
<title>Professional publishing architecture (how doc teams scale)</title>
<p>As documentation grows, teams typically separate concerns:</p>
<ul>
  <li><b>Authoring repo</b> (topics, maps, reuse, media)</li>
  <li><b>Build system repo</b> (pipeline scripts, configs)</li>
  <li><b>Brand/theme repo</b> (CSS, templates, PDF themes)</li>
  <li><b>Deployment system</b> (portal, CDN, internal hosting)</li>
</ul>
<p>This separation:</p>
<ul>
  <li>keeps authors focused,</li>
  <li>keeps customization controlled,</li>
  <li>supports multiple brands/products.</li>
</ul>
</section>
<section id="a-practical-starter-publishing-setup-copyable-blueprint">
<title>A practical “starter publishing setup” (copyable blueprint)</title>
<p><b>Suggested folder layout</b></p>
<codeblock>dita/
  maps/
  topics/
  reuse/
  media/
  ditaval/
  build/
    build.sh
    build.ps1
    params/
      html.properties
      pdf.properties</codeblock>
<p><b>What goes where</b></p>
<ul>
  <li><codeph>maps/</codeph>: deliverable definitions</li>
  <li><codeph>topics/</codeph>: content</li>
  <li><codeph>reuse/</codeph>: shared snippets</li>
  <li><codeph>ditaval/</codeph>: filtering rules per variant</li>
  <li><codeph>build/</codeph>: scripts + parameters</li>
</ul>
<p><b>Build script responsibilities</b></p>
<ul>
  <li>pick input maps,</li>
  <li>pick output formats,</li>
  <li>apply filter rules,</li>
  <li>pass consistent parameters,</li>
  <li>place outputs in a clean directory.</li>
</ul>
</section>
<section id="common-publishing-mistakes-and-how-to-avoid-them">
<title>Common publishing mistakes (and how to avoid them)</title>
<p><b>Mistake: Publishing topics directly instead of maps</b></p>
<p>Fix: publish maps so key spaces and navigation context are consistent.</p>
<p><b>Mistake: Customizing too early</b></p>
<p>Fix: start with minimal overrides; grow customization as requirements become clear.</p>
<p><b>Mistake: Not treating build warnings as serious</b></p>
<p>Fix: fail builds on unresolved references and broken conrefs; monitor warning counts.</p>
<p><b>Mistake: No repeatability</b></p>
<p>Fix: scripts/project files; document required DITA‑OT version and plugins.</p>
<p><b>Mistake: Mixing build outputs into source</b></p>
<p>Fix: separate <codeph>out/</codeph> from source and keep it out of version control.</p>
</section>
<section id="analytics-instrumentation">
<title>Analytics and Instrumentation</title>
<p>Instrument publishing outputs to track which formats and outputs are most used. Use analytics to identify popular outputs and troubleshoot publishing issues.</p>
</section>
<section id="personalization-conditional-processing">
<title>Personalization and Conditional Processing</title>
<p>Use DITA conditional processing to generate branded or generic outputs. Example:</p>
<codeblock outputclass="language-xml">&lt;section product="acme"&gt;Acme-branded output instructions.&lt;/section&gt;</codeblock>
</section>
<section id="chatbot-nlp-integration">
<title>Integrating with Conversational AI and NLP</title>
<p>Integrate publishing FAQs and troubleshooting steps with chatbots to provide instant support for publishing issues.</p>
</section>
<section id="continuous-improvement-feedback">
<title>Continuous Improvement and Feedback Loops</title>
<p>Add a feedback widget to publishing documentation. Use analytics and user feedback to improve publishing instructions and resolve common pain points.</p>
</section>
  </conbody>
</concept>
